<br>
I have; however, been on more than one raid on Cazic Thule where a human team group of usually less than 6 has been able to roust the people there and then hold the zone to camp.  On one occasion we had some who did not abide by Loot and Scoot but for the most part it was an exciting and even pleasant feeling to gain contorl and added to the delight when a Ravenscale helm dropped (it went to fellow rogue, Plumber).<br>
<br>
Don't let those who say things &quot;can't be done&quot; fool you.  Not only were we able to gain access to a territory deep into &quot;enemy lands&quot; but we were able to do it with a pure team group.<br>
<br>
~Fricka <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umresone.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mresone</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/21/01 8:40:59 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ravenscale</span><hr size=1> I have both pieces of RS that I own from the cooling corpses of the critters what drop them.<br>
<br>
CT is definately a workable dungeon.  Actually, playing in some one else's sand-box is much more satisfying than playing in *safe* zones.  You just have to take a group down there.  You cannot expect to waltz into the dungeon and shout &quot;LVL 30 ELF ROGUE LFG!!!&quot;<br>
<br>
